For those who typically dont consider themselves "cruise people," the best cruises often feature unique itineraries, a focus on immersive experiences, and a more relaxed atmosphere. Here are some options that might appeal to non-traditional cruisers:

1. Small Ship Cruises

  • Examples: Windstar, UnCruise Adventures, and SeaDream Yacht Club
  • Why: Smaller ships allow for more personalized service, intimate settings, and access to less-visited ports that larger ships can't reach. They often offer a more relaxed, casual vibe.

Start with a short cruise,may be 3 or 5 days. Pick the type of ship you prefer,either small and intimate,medium size or gigantic. Read up and learn about the ship itself like how many dinning rooms,buffet service,size of cabins,itinerary and look for good or bad comments people leave on the site.

Naive folks might recommend a sampler cruise - this is something that leaves a port, wanders around the ocean for 34 days, not stopping at any other ports, and returning to the original. Unfortunately, these are also known as booze cruises. I did one (in a suite, just to bump Frequent cruiser points to the next level) and a crew member pointed out that of the 3000 passengers about 2400 had bought the unlimited drinks deal. I would have seen at least a dozen drunk passengers being confined to their cabins by ship security to sleep it off.

I suppose the answer would more depend on what the non-cruise people enjoy doing. If being very active is their preference (vs lying on the beach or around the pool), a port-intensive Mediterranean cruise or river cruise might be good choices. With these cruises, theres a new place to explore almost every day, with the convenience of going back to what is effectively a moving hotel with restaurants and entertainment. Other potentially interesting options might be cruises that circle Japan or the U.K.

Which cruise company do you recommend for someone who has never been on a cruise before?

I would recommend booking a cruise according to your interests and energy level. Lets start with bargain cruises for those who just want to get away to a beach and party. Carnival has the corner on that market with Norwegian Cruises close behind.

If youre looking for the next price point, Princess would be my recommendation.

For those who enjoy elaborate theme parties, a wider variety of meal-choices and are traveling with families, definitely Royal Caribbean!! They are non-stop fun and yet, they keep it classy!

What should I know before taking a cruise?

I have taken around ten cruises, and when I retire in a few years, intend to take at least that many more. It is, in my opinion, the most restful, romantic, and thoroughly delightful experience that remains affordable to average income individuals. However, there are indeed several things you should know before you embark.

  1. Unless drinking and nightlife are your main objective, stay away from "party boats" run by Carnival. The food is like a Golden Corral, and this cruiseline is frequented by those who like to booze it up.
